      "role": "user",
      "content": "wait what does goblin-proof mean? that sounds weird. can you just stick to the legal side? i'm trying to figure out if this makes me personally liable for their legal fees if a third party sues them because of something i did.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the legal aspect.\n\nIn the context of the indemnification clause, \"goblin-proof\" is a colloquialism that means you're taking on the responsibility of protecting the Disclosing Party from any potential losses or damages. However, in a more literal sense, the clause is stating that you'll be responsible for paying any losses or damages that the Disclosing Party incurs as a result of your actions or inactions under the agreement.\n\nRegarding your question, the indemnification clause typically includes language that limits the Recipient's (your) liability to the Disclosing Party's (their) losses or damages. This means that if a third party sues the Disclosing Party because of something you did, and the court finds you liable, you might be required to pay the Disclosing Party's legal fees, but only up to the amount of the Disclosing Party's losses or damages.\n\nHowever, the clause usually includes a provision that requires you to indemnify the Disclosing Party for their \"reasonable attorneys' fees\" and \"costs.\" This means that even if you're not directly liable for the losses or damages, you might still be required to pay the Disc",
