    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay i see. so basically if i make a mistake, i'm on the hook for their lawyers too. that sounds pretty risky. are there any specific red flags or \"hidden\" things in this kind of language that usually trip people up or catch them off guard?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The indemnification clause can be a bit tricky, and there are some common pitfalls to watch out for. One thing to be cautious of is the phrase \"reasonable attorneys' fees.\" This can be a bit subjective, and the Disclosing Party might try to argue that their lawyers' fees are \"reasonable\" even if they're not.\n\nAnother potential issue is the lack of specificity regarding what constitutes \"negligence or willful misconduct.\" This can lead to disputes over whether your actions were truly negligent or willful, and whether you're liable for the Disclosing Party's losses.\n\nAdditionally, some indemnification clauses might include language that requires you to indemnify the Disclosing Party for \"all\" of their losses, rather than just those that are \"directly\" or \"proximately\" caused by your actions. This can be a bit of a trap, as it might make you liable for losses that are not directly related to your actions.\n\nIt's also worth noting that some indemnification clauses might include a \"cap\" on the amount of damages you're liable for. For example, the clause might state that you'll only be liable for \"up to $X\" in damages. However, this can be a bit of a trap, as",
